**▶ Watch it get built** — this page is the demo. The roadmap and changelog *are* the product right now.

---

## The Pitch

**Problem.** Most of my systems show up here finished. This one doesn't — and that's the point. Training is a domain where I have real data flowing (workouts logged in Hevy, calories and macros logged in Fitbee, a weekly weigh-in) but no system tying it together yet. The honest move isn't to fake a polished case study; it's to put the half-built thing on the wall and let the changelog do the talking. Every other portfolio shows you the highlight reel. This page shows you the work in progress.

**System.** The blueprint is a standardization loop, built in stages: **ingest** the raw signals — workouts from a **Hevy** CSV export and nutrition actuals (calories + macros) from **Fitbee**, joined to the weekly weigh-in — then a **weekly programming loop** where the AI drafts next week's training from last week's *actuals* and a human approves it, a **monthly performance-review memo**, and a **quarterly program redesign**. Today only the early pieces exist; the rest is roadmap. The maturity score says 2 and means it — that's not an apology, it's the spec.

**Payoff.** Two things. First, the practical one: a training system that programs itself from what I actually did, not what some generic plan assumed. Second, the meta one — this is what "build in public" looks like done honestly. A portfolio that shows a `2/5` getting built, with visible velocity in the changelog, is more credible than one where everything is suspiciously finished. Immaturity, labeled and moving, becomes a reason to come back and check on it.

---

## The Loops

| Cadence | What happens | Automation |
|---|---|---|
| Continuous | Ingest — workouts (Hevy CSV export) + calories/macros (Fitbee), joined to the weekly weigh-in *(v1 loop being defined)* | **full** *(planned)* |
| Weekly | Programming loop — AI drafts next week from last week's actuals | **human-approve** |
| Weekly | Weigh-in + calorie adjustment vs the 12-week glide path | **human-approve** |
| Monthly | Performance-review memo — trends, adherence, what to change | **full** (draft), **human-approve** (act) |
| Quarterly | Program redesign | **human-approve** |

*Honest labeling: the weekly weigh-in / macro-adjustment cadence is **established and running today**; the automated ingest and programming loops are **defined but not yet built** — flagged `(planned)` above rather than dressed up as live.*

---

## AI Architecture

Three named roles, most of which are still on the roadmap — stated as the design, not a claim of current state:

- **Ingest.** Normalizes the raw exports — the **Hevy** workout CSV and **Fitbee** nutrition log — into a clean weekly picture of actuals: what got trained (sets, loads, RPE), calories and protein actually logged, and the bodyweight trend from the weekly weigh-in. The foundation everything else reads from. *(v1 in definition.)*
- **Programmer.** The weekly draft engine: takes last week's actuals and proposes next week's training and macro targets. Deliberately a *draft* — it never auto-applies.
- **Reviewer.** Writes the monthly performance-review memo from the trend data and flags what to change heading into the next block.

**Where the human gate sits.** This is a heavily human-gated system by design, which fits a domain where the cost of a bad automated call is real fatigue or injury. Ingest and the memo draft can run automatically; **every programming and nutrition change is human-approve.** The AI proposes the week; the human accepts it. That's the right posture for a training system and it's stated up front rather than discovered later.

*Data posture (R7): this page surfaces **trends and adherence %**, never raw body data. No weights, no measurements, no raw health numbers — just whether the system is being followed and which direction the trend points.*

---

## The Flowchart

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  EXPORT["Hevy CSV (workouts)<br/>+ Fitbee (nutrition)"] --> INGEST["Ingest<br/>(normalize actuals)"]
  INGEST --> ACTUALS[("Last week's actuals")]
  ACTUALS --> PROG["Programmer<br/>drafts next week"]
  PROG --> GATE{"Human<br/>approve?"}
  GATE -->|approved| WEEK["Next week's<br/>training + macros"]
  GATE -->|adjust| PROG
  WEEK --> TRAIN["Train + log<br/>(Hevy + Fitbee)"]
  TRAIN --> EXPORT
  ACTUALS --> MEMO["Reviewer<br/>monthly memo"]
  MEMO --> QTR["Quarterly redesign"]
  QTR -.->|resets| PROG
  TRAIN --> METRICS["Adherence % · trends"]
  METRICS --> HEART[("Heartbeat")]
```

---

## Challenges & Lessons

- **Publishing it at a `2/5` is the harder choice, and the right one.** The instinct is to wait until it's impressive. But a portfolio whose only failure mode is "everything's finished" reads as a highlight reel, and senior readers discount highlight reels. Shipping a labeled, honestly-immature system — with the changelog as the proof of motion — is a credibility play, not a confession. The lesson generalizes: visible velocity on an unfinished system beats a static finished-looking one.
- **Start the loop deliberately small.** The temptation with fitness data is to ingest *everything* — every set, every macro, every adherence signal — and build the grand programmer on day one. That's how this kind of project dies: too much surface, never ships. The v1 loop is being defined as the *smallest* thing that closes: pull the Hevy export + Fitbee actuals → draft a week → approve. Earn complexity later. The real signal worth catching early is the known failure mode — under-logging and protein slipping below target — which a tight loop surfaces fast.
- **Privacy is a design constraint, not an afterthought.** Health data is the most sensitive thing any of my systems touch. The decision to surface only **trends and adherence %** — never raw body metrics — is baked into the architecture from the start (R7), not bolted on before launch. Deciding that early shapes what the heartbeat is even allowed to carry.
- **What I'd redo.** Nothing yet — that's the honest answer for a system this early, and saying so is more credible than inventing a war story. The "what I'd redo" will fill in as the loops actually run. *(Revisit this section after the first month of real cycles.)*

